Does modern medicine increase life-expectancy: Quest for the Moon Rabbit?

Mishra S(1).

Author information:
(1)Professor, Department of Cardiology, AIIMS, New Delhi, India. Electronic 
address: sundeepmishraihj@gmail.com.

The search for elixir of immortality has yielded mixed results. While some of 
the interventions like percutaneous coronary interventions and coronary artery 
bypass grafting have been a huge disappointment at least as far as prolongation 
of life is concerned, their absolute benefit is meager and that too in very sick 
patients. Cardiac specific drugs like statins and aspirin have fared slightly 
better, being useful in patients with manifest coronary artery disease, 
particularly in sicker populations although even their usefulness in primary 
prevention is rather low. The only strategies of proven benefit in 
primary/primordial prevention are pursuing a healthy life-style and its 
modification when appropriate, like cessation of smoking, weight reduction, 
increasing physical activity, eating a healthy diet and bringing blood pressure, 
serum cholesterol, and blood glucose under control.

